<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-225-322 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 407 264</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 5 1991 v5 n5 p80(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hayes case: minor impact expected. (Hayes Microcomputer ProductsInc's patent infringement case)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hayes Microcomputer Products Inc. (Patents)Everex Systems Inc. (Cases)OmniTel Inc. (Cases)Ven-Tel Inc. (Cases).andO;Ticker:    EVRX.andO;Topic:     Law SuitPatentModems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Carolyn SaidandM;San Francisco -- Last week's decision by a federal jury here that threecompanies deliberately infringed on patents held by Hayes MicrocomputerProducts Inc. will not result in major fallout for users and modemdevelopers, experts said.andM;The jury awarded Hayes $3.5 million in damages -- an amount that the judgecould triple -- to be paid by three manufacturers of Hayes-compatible modems:Everex Systems Inc. of Fremont, Calif.; Omnitel Inc. of Santa Clara, Calif.;andO;and Ven-Tel Inc. of San Jose, Calif.andP;  The companies plan to appeal.andM;While Hayes and industry observers said the decision should spur theapproximately 300 manufacturers of Hayes-compatible modems to sign licensingagreements with Hayes, they predicted that effects would be negligible.andM;&quot;Consumers won't see an impact&quot; from the 1.75 percent royalty rate set by thefederal jury, according to Larry Cynar, senior industry analyst at DataquestInc. of San Jose.andM;Although Hayes technically could refuse licenses to modem companies,effectively blocking them from distributing Hayes-compatible modems, &quot;Hayeshas no interest in stopping anyone from manufacturing [modems],&quot; according toDennis Hayes, founder and president of the company.andM;Nor are companies likely to try circumventing Hayes' patents, industryexperts said.andP;  &quot;The AT-command set is very mature and widely accepted.andP;  Ithink it would be rather difficult [to work around the patents],&quot; said DaleWalsh, vice president of advanced development at U.S.andP;  Robotics Inc. ofSkokie, Ill.andM;The patent in question covers the escape mechanism implemented in every HayesSmartmodem.andP;  &quot;If a modem really is Hayes-compatible, there is a very goodchance it would infringe the patent,&quot; Hayes said.andM;The company holds more than 40 patents on technology implemented in itsmodems.andP;  The Smartmodem, introduced in 1981, was the first &quot;intelligent&quot;modem capable of automatically dialing, answering and responding to commandsunder computer control.andM;Hayes said 17 modem manufacturers have licensed the patent, including twocompanies that took licenses immediately before the San Francisco trialbegan.andM;Intellectual-property rights will be most affected by the verdict, expertssaid.andP;  &quot;People hire good minds to develop these things; they have a right tobe protected,&quot; Cynar said.andM;&quot;This says there is protection for companies who invent new technology andsolve problems for customers,&quot; Hayes said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>